---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Security | BeaconGuard Fail-Closed AI Policy Enforcement"
  description="BeaconGuard is designed for fail-closed policy enforcement, approval gates, sensitive data handling, and evidence integrity in regulated AI operations."
>
  <section class="stack-section">
    <h1>Security</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard keeps model behavior out of the authorization layer by placing deterministic policy checks before AI or automation execution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>The Control Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Large Language Models (LLMs) are probabilistic generation engines. They cannot serve as the authorization boundary for regulated operations where security, privacy, compliance, audit, or risk teams need explicit control before execution.
      Relying on prompt engineering alone to govern sensitive data handling, customer-impacting recommendations, or regulated internal automation creates operational risk.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Policy-Enforced AI Ingress</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard Assurance enforces a deterministic control boundary before model inference. Requests are evaluated for trust, structural validity, data sensitivity, user role, workflow scope, and policy compliance before the LLM is invoked.
      Untrusted, malformed, replayed, or out-of-policy requests are blocked from reaching the model.
    </p>
    <div class="infra-diagram">
      <div class="flow-diagram flow-diagram--sequence-3 security-workflow">
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform flow-node-primary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">Untrusted / malformed / replayed request</p>
          <p>Ingress validation runs before policy evaluation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform flow-node-boundary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">BeaconGuard deterministic boundary</p>
          <p>Trust, structure, and policy checks execute in the same controlled control layer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform flow-node-deny">
          <p class="flow-step-title">Blocked before model inference</p>
          <p>Denied requests do not proceed to model output.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flow-diagram flow-diagram--sequence-2 security-workflow" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform flow-node-primary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">Trusted / valid / policy-compliant request</p>
          <p>Inbound trust checks pass and request enters enforcement.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</div>
        <div class="flow-step flow-step--uniform flow-node-boundary">
          <p class="flow-step-title">BeaconGuard deterministic boundary</p>
          <p>Model invocation only after allow decision.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="flow-path-note">
        The model remains outside the control boundary and only receives requests that pass deterministic enforcement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Fail-Closed Enforcement</h2>
    <p>
      When required policy conditions are not met, BeaconGuard executes a deterministic, fail-closed denial. The system prevents AI or automation from creating an unauthorized forward path and preserves human-reviewed operational authority where approval is required.
    </p>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Deterministic Deny</h3>
        <p>Missing trust proofs, invalid structure, or policy gaps resolve to deny, not permissive fallback.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Approval Gates</h3>
        <p>Requests that require human review can be routed as needs-review before execution proceeds.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Least-Privilege AI Execution</h3>
        <p>Policy can limit which users, roles, workflows, systems, and data types are allowed to trigger model invocation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Evidence Integrity</h3>
        <p>Decision records preserve the policy identity, request context, outcome, and reason needed for later review.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Designed for Regulated Review Environments</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard is designed to produce evidence useful to security, privacy, compliance, and audit teams in workflows where uncontrolled AI execution is not acceptable.
      It separates policy enforcement from model response and does not claim certifications, legal compliance guarantees, or replacement of internal control programs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Where to go next</h2>
    <p><a href="/trust-assurance">Trust Center</a></p>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/proof-evidence">Reviewable Decision Evidence</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/canonical-workflow">Workflow Examples</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    @media (max-width: 900px) {
      .security-workflow {
        display: block;
        gap: 0;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-step {
        width: 100%;
        min-height: 0;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-step-title {
        font-size: 0.98rem;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-arrow {
        display: none;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-step + .flow-step {
        margin-top: 1.2rem;
        position: relative;
        padding-top: 1.35rem;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-step + .flow-step::before {
        content: "";
        position: absolute;
        left: 50%;
        top: -0.62rem;
        transform: translateX(-50%);
        width: 2px;
        height: 0.75rem;
        background: var(--brand-accent);
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-step + .flow-step::after {
        content: "↓";
        position: absolute;
        left: 50%;
        top: -0.6rem;
        transform: translate(-50%, -65%);
        font-size: 0.9rem;
        line-height: 1;
        color: var(--brand-accent);
        font-weight: 700;
      }

      .security-workflow .flow-node-boundary {
        border-left: 4px solid var(--brand-accent);
        box-shadow: 0 0 0 1px rgba(91, 155, 224, 0.2);
      }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
